[5] Philippines
Date: 3 Jun 2009
Source: MB.com.ph [edited]
<http://www.mb.com.ph/articles/205649/antidengue-campaign-launched>


Health Secretary Francisco T. Duque III launched Wednesday [3 Jun
2009] a nationwide anti-dengue campaign, reiterating that dengue is
more dangerous than influenza A (H1N1).

The campaign, dubbed as "Ako, Ikaw, Tayong Lahat Laban sa Dengue,"
was meant to increase the public's awareness on the 4S strategy of
the DoH to avoid dengue-carrying mosquitoes. The 4-S stands for
Search and Destroy, Self-protection, Seek early treatment and Say no
to indiscriminate fogging.

Earlier, Duque emphasized that dengue is "more fatal" than influenza A (H1N1).

"Right now, what we're seeing from the behavior of the virus (H1N1)
is that most of the cases are mild and are self-limiting. The case
fatality rate of H1N1, in fact, is less than one percent. Dengue is
even more fatal in the country, where we now have 57 deaths as of
April this year [2009]," he said.

The DoH disease surveillance report showed that from January to 9 May
[2009], there were a total of 6537 cases of dengue with 62 deaths as
compared to the same period last year [2008], with 15 334 cases and 163 deaths.

The figures reveal a 57.4 percent decrease in the number of dengue
cases compared to 2008.

"With the 4S strategy that was widely disseminated in communities and
schools last year [2008], people became more aware of how easy it was
to prevent the spread of the dengue-carrying mosquitoes," Duque said.

The highest number of dengue cases was in the National Capital Region
with 1174 cases; Davao region 1085; Calabarzon, 807; and Central
Visayas, 636 cases.

Clustering of dengue cases were seen in 3 or more barangays during
the past 4 weeks in the following areas: Metro Manila (Sampaloc,
Tondo, Novaliches, Dagat-dagatan); Calabarzon (Lucena City, Taytay);
Negros Occidental (Bacolod City); Cebu (Naga City, Lapu-Lapu City)
and Davao City, among others. [Barangays are the smallest
administrative division in the Philippines and is the Filipino term
for a village, district or ward. - Mod.TY]

[Byline: Jenny F. Manongdo]

