[7] Saudi Arabia
Date: Thu 28 May 2009
Source: Saudi Wave [edited]
<http://www.saudiwave.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1032:the-mermaid-of-the-red-sea-swims-in-a-sea-of-sewage&catid=84:interior-affairs&Itemid=182>


Several newspapers and websites have rung alarm bells and warned
against a new epidemic of dengue fever, [caused by] a virus mainly
transmitted by mosquitoes that decimates mainly the animal but also
the human population. [Animals in Saudi Arabia would not be affected
by dengue virus infection. - Mod.TY]

"A horror gripped the people of Saudi Arabia after the appearance of
the dengue fever cases in Jeddah and Mecca," Mohamed Sayed Ali had
reported on 13 Apr 2009 on "Islamonline."

Quoting government medical sources, the official Saudi press agency
SPA had at the time announced "33 cases of dengue fever illness in
Jeddah and 103 in Mecca since the beginning of the month" [April 2009].

The daily "Okaz" had, on 12 Apr 2009, reported that a Saudi man and
woman, aged respectively 20 and 22 years old and afflicted by the
virus, had finally succumbed the previous day at King Faisal hospital in Mecca.

The following day, other newspapers had reported the hospitalization
in Mecca of more than 100 people affected by the disease. Most of
them were discharged from the hospitals after receiving emergency treatment.

